      "body" : "OK, I understand.  Would it make more sense to, er, \"crash gracefully\" rather than presenting an assert message to the end-user though?\r\n\r\n@luke-jr the \"assert.h\" file (gnu for example) has code like this:\r\n #ifdef NDEBUG\r\n #define assert(EX)\r\n #else\r\n #define assert(EX) (void)((EX) || (__assert (#EX, __FILE__, __LINE__),0))\r\n #endif \r\n\r\nso if you #define NDEBUG somewhere in your code it basically makes the assert macro do nothing.  It's meant to disable debugging mode.  I was unclear on whether the -g option also did this but it does not.  ",
      "created_at" : "2013-08-29T19:37:30Z",
